<DOC><DOCNO> AP890823-0163 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-89 2055EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-23 0542</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0556</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Indiana, Illinois</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Powerful thunderstorms in Indiana and Illinois on Wednesdayspawned flooding, winds that knocked out power to thousands andlightning that blasted a car on an interstate highway and gouged ahole in the road.   Rain-triggered floods in West Virginia closed roads and swamped afire house and other buildings.   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell in New England, NewYork, South Carolina, Georgia and the eastern and central Gulf Coast.   Showers fell on the northern Rockies and the northern and centralIntermountain region between the Rockies and the Sierra Nevada andthe mountains of eastern Oregon.   Thunderstorms continued dropping heavy rain on sections of theOhio Valley on Wednesday afternoon. A morning storm dropped 1{ inchof rain in the western Indiana city of Crawfordsville.   The rain flooded two state highways in Shelby County, Ind.,southeast of Indianapolis, and homes and streets in Champaign Countyin eastern Illinois. A flash-flood watch was in effect for centralIndiana.   Lightning hit an automobile on Interstate 74 in MontgomeryCounty, which includes Crawfordsville, but the car's occupants werenot seriously hurt. The strike left a hole 2{ feet wide and 1{ feetdeep.   Lightning or wind knocked out power to 4,000 homes in ChampaignCounty, as well as two University of Illinois dormitories inChampaign-Urbana on the first day of classes. Power was also knockedout near rural Mayfield, Ky.   Thunderstorm winds blew down a work shed in the central Illinoiscity of Taylorville, and blew down trees south of Coal City inwestern Indiana. Nickel-size hail also fell in Coal City.   In central West Virginia, high water closed roads in UpshurCounty and flooded a fire house in Selbyville, a store in Pickensand homes in Helvetia. Water was 2 feet over a road in Newlon. Aflash-flood watch was in effect in all of West Virginia except thepanhandles.   The rain in the West was generated by a strong cold front thatwas expected to bring snow to higher elevations of western Wyoming.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51degrees in Klamath Falls, Ore., to around 100 degrees in Beeville,Texas. The low for the lower 48 states Wednesday morning was 33degrees in Gunnison, Colo.   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from themiddle and southern Atlantic Coast to Florida, the eastern andcentral Gulf Coast, the Tennessee Valley, the southern half of thelower Ohio Valley and the lower Mississippi Valley; scatteredshowers and thunderstorms over the northern High Plains, thenorthern and central Rockies, and the region between the mountainsof eastern Oregon and Washington, with strong, gusty winds over thecentral Rockies.   High temperatures were expected in the 90s across much of thenation, the 60s in northern New England, along the southern shore ofLake Superior and in the northern Rockies; in the 70s along thePacific Coast; in the 70s and 80s from inland northern California toNevada and the central and southern Rockies, and from the northernPlains to the upper Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes, theOhio Valley and much of the middle and northern Atlantic Coast; andbetween 100 and 110 degrees in the desert Southwest.</TEXT></DOC>